Marker¶

In [ ]:
You can use the keyword argument marker to emphasize each point with a specified marker:
In [12]:
In [17]:
x1=[1,2,3,4,5,6,7]
y2=[30,17,40,45,25,20,20]
plt.plot(x1,y1, marker='H', color='yellow', markeredgecolor='r')
plt.show()

Marker Description¶

'o' Circle
'*' Star
'.' Point
',' Pixel
'x' X
'X' X (filled)
'+' Plus
'P' Plus (filled)
's' Square
'D' Diamond 'd' Diamond (thin)
'p' Pentagon
'H' Hexagon 'h' Hexagon 'v' Triangle Down
'^' Triangle Up '<' Triangle Left
'>' Triangle Right
'1' Tri Down
'2' Tri Up
'3' Tri Left
'4' Tri Right
'|' Vline
'_' Hline

==================================Line Syntax Description¶

'-' Solid line
':' Dotted line '--' Dashed line '-.' Dashed/dotted line

In [18]:
ypoints = np.array([3, 8, 1, 10])

plt.plot(ypoints, 'o:r')
plt.show()

Set Font Properties for Title and Labels FONT¶

In [ ]:
Font= Fondict
In [54]:
x=[4,6,8,10,12]
y=[10,12,14,16,18]
plt.plot(a,b,marker='H',color='Green',markeredgecolor='red')

font1 = {'family':'serif','color':'blue','size':40}
font2 = {'family':'serif','color':'darkred','size':50}


plt.title('Practice plot', fontdict=font2)
plt.xlabel('X-AXIS', fontdict= font1)
plt.ylabel('Y-AXIS', fontdict=font1)
plt.show()

Scatter()¶

In [ ]:
The scatter() function plots one dot for each observation. It needs two arrays of the same length, one for the values of 
the x-axis, and one for values on the y-axis:
In [93]:
a=[1,2,3,4,5]
b=[10,20,30,40,50]
plt.scatter(a,b)
plt.show()

ColorMap--scatter¶

In [ ]:
A colormap is like a list of colors, where each color has a value that ranges from 0 to 10
This colormap is called 'viridis' and as you can see it ranges from 0, which is a purple color, up to 100,
which is a yellow color.
In [104]:
x = [5,7,8,7,2,17,2,9,4,11,12,9,6]
y = [99,86,87,88,111,86,103,87,94,78,77,85,86]
colors = np.array([0, 10, 20, 30, 40, 45, 50, 55, 60, 70, 80, 90, 100])

plt.scatter(x, y, c=colors, cmap='viridis')

plt.show()
In [105]:
x = [5,7,8,7,2,17,2,9,4,11,12,9,6]
y = [99,86,87,88,111,86,103,87,94,78,77,85,86]
colors = np.array([0, 10, 20, 30, 40, 45, 50, 55, 60, 70, 80, 90, 100])

plt.scatter(x, y, c=colors, cmap='viridis')
plt.colorbar()
plt.show()

size - change size of scatter dots¶

You can change the size of the dots with the 's' argument.

In [110]:
#You can change the size of the dots with the 's' argument.
x = [5,7,8,7,2,17,2,9,4,11,12,9,6]
y = [99,86,87,88,111,86,103,87,94,78,77,85,86]
size = np.array([20,50,100,200,500,1000,60,90,10,300,600,800,75])

plt.scatter(x, y,s=size)
#plt.colorbar()
plt.show()

Alpha===scatter¶

you can change the transparency of dots with the help of alpha arguments

In [113]:
x = [5,7,8,7,2,17,2,9,4,11,12,9,6]
y = [99,86,87,88,111,86,103,87,94,78,77,85,86]
size = np.array([20,50,100,200,500,1000,60,90,10,300,600,800,75])

plt.scatter(x, y, s=size, alpha=0.5)
#plt.colorbar()
plt.show()

Combine Color Size and Alpha¶

In [ ]:
You can combine a colormap with different sizes of the dots. This is best visualized if the dots are transparent:
Create random arrays with 100 values for x-points, y-points, colors and sizes:
In [114]:
x = np.random.randint(100, size=(100))
y = np.random.randint(100, size=(100))
colors = np.random.randint(100, size=(100))
sizes = 10 * np.random.randint(100, size=(100))

plt.scatter(x, y, c=colors, s=sizes, alpha=0.5, cmap='nipy_spectral')

plt.colorbar()

plt.show()

Matplotlib Pie Charts¶

PIE======= Lables Start Angles Explode Shadow colors Legend With Header

In [120]:
p=[23,45,67]             #Simple PIE
plt.pie(p)
plt.show()

Label¶

Add labels to the pie chart with the "Labels" parameter. The label parameter must be an array with one label for each wedge:

In [122]:
p=[23,45,67,45]    
mylabels = ["Apples", "Bananas", "Cherries", "Dates"]
plt.pie(p,labels=mylabels)
plt.show()

Start Angle¶

As mentioned the default start angle is at the x-axis, but you can change the start angle by specifying a startangle parameter. The startangle parameter is defined with an angle in degrees, default angle is 0:

In [124]:
p=[23,45,67,45]    
mylabels = ["Apples", "Bananas", "Cherries", "Dates"]

plt.pie(p,labels=mylabels, startangle= 90)

plt.show()

Explode¶

It shows each value represents how far from the center each wedge is displayed:it pulls the parameters

In [ ]:
#Example
#Pull the "Apples" wedge 0.2 from the center of the pie:
In [126]:
p=[23,45,67,45]    
mylabels = ["Apples", "Bananas", "Cherries", "Dates"]
myexplode=[0.2,0,0,0]

plt.pie(p,labels=mylabels, explode=myexplode)
plt.show()

Shadow¶

Add a shadow to the pie chart by setting the shadows parameter to True:

In [127]:
p=[23,45,67,45]    
mylabels = ["Apples", "Bananas", "Cherries", "Dates"]
myexplode=[0.2,0,0,0]

plt.pie(p,labels=mylabels, explode=myexplode, shadow= True)
plt.show()

Colors¶

Example Specify a new color for each wedge:

In [130]:
y=[34,45,3,4]
mylabels = ["Apples", "Bananas", "Cherries", "Dates"]
mycolors = ["black", "hotpink", "b", "#4CAF50"]
plt.pie(y,labels=mylabels, colors=mycolors)
plt.show()

Legend¶

To add a list of explanation for each wedge, use the legend() function:

In [134]:
y=[34,45,3,4]
mylabels = ["Apples", "Bananas", "Cherries", "Dates"]
mycolors = ["black", "hotpink", "b", "#4CAF50"]
plt.pie(y,labels=mylabels, colors=mycolors,autopct='%d%%')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Legend With Header¶

To add a header to the legend, add the "title" parameter to the legend function.

In [133]:
y=[34,45,3,4]
mylabels = ["Apples", "Bananas", "Cherries", "Dates"]
mycolors = ["black", "hotpink", "b", "#4CAF50"]
plt.pie(y,labels=mylabels, colors=mycolors)
plt.legend(title='four fruits')
plt.show()
